public class java_46877_SessionManager_A07 {  // Class definition starts here (f)
    private Map<String, String> sessionMap = new HashMap<>();   // Use of standard library 'Hashmap', which is efficient for storing key-value pairs. It also uses synchronization internally to prevent concurrent modification exceptions during operations such as get or put map entries due to potential multithreaded scenarios
    private Object lockObj;  // Lock object used in conjunction with the sessionsMap, ensures thread safety while manipulating sessionmap (e) - Note: This should be an instance variable for this specific use case. A common practice is providing a static 'lock' if you only want to synchronize methods that access our SessionManager
    
    public String createSession(String userId){   // Method definition starts here (d), note the explicit type of method return as void in modern Java style, unless there are specific error handling needs. We will assume we have a successful session creation for this case – A07_AuthFailure related scenario is not mentioned
        synchronized(lockObj) {   // Synchronize when accessing shared resources (e). Note that 'this' can be used if the above lockObject isn’t static but in real-world scenarios, we may want to use a different mechanism depending on our specific needs. A07_AuthFailure is not mentioned here
            sessionMap.put(userId, "SESSION_" + userId); // Simulate successful creation of Session by storing it under the key (UserID) - Note: This should be replaced with actual logic for creating sessions and handling failures during this process – A07_AuthFailure related scenario is not mentioned here
            System.out.println("Created session " + userId);   // Simulate successful creation of Session by printing a message to console (Note, we don't actually have an Auth failure error as per the task requirements) - Note: This should be replaced with actual logic for logging errors and handling failures during this process – A07_AuthFailure related scenario is not mentioned here
        }   // End of synchronization block. Again note that 'this'. If we are using static lock in real world, then it would probably use a different mechanism than shown below (a). This line ensures thread safety while accessing sessionMap between multiple threads when they enter the method at same time – A07_AuthFailure related scenario is not mentioned here.
        return "Created Session"; // Assuming that all operations are successful, this will be returned from our methods - Note: Depending on actual use case and error handling needs we might need to replace with specific code for returning sessionId or an exception – A07_AuthFailure related scenario is not mentioned here.
    }   // End of method definition (d)
    
}//End Class Definition(f). This will be the end point where you can start executing methods in java file, and this should work with modern Java style as per requirements provided above – A07_AuthFailure related scenario is not mentioned here. Also note that we assume a single threaded environment due to simplicity of explanation but real world scenarios may require more complexity (like multi-threading or async operations).